  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Ethiopia: Strengthening human rights monitoring</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Repression of civil society in Ethiopia had become progressively worse as of 2014, when the CSO law severely limited nongovernmental organizations to work on human rights, good governance and conflict resolution. Our local partner in Ethiopia at that time - as most other human rights and civil society organisations - had been affected but managed to continue its work on investigating forced evictions, arbitrary arrests, extra-judicial executions and more. With civil society in Ethiopia nearly decimated, our partner was one of the last standing human rights organisations in the country that managed to share information. Late 2015, the partner contacted Amnesty International with the request to strengthen the capacity of their monitoring teams in monitoring human rights violations, to strengthen their evidence collection and credibility, and to produce stronger reports in appealing for the international community to respond. Within this context, AINL/HURICAP trained human rights monitors from our partner in the basics of human rights law, skills and knowledge of monitoring violations and basic safety &amp; security techniques. Political changes in 2018-2019, which let to the opening up of civic space in the country, also meant that the project had to be refocused completely. As this was around the time of the Mid-Term Review, we made a concerted decision not to refocus capacity-building work for human rights defenders in Ethiopia, but instead to strengthen the country programmes that are already in the implementation phase. New programmes would probably not be able to achieve the desired outcomes in the remaining timeframe of this Strategic Partnership.</narrative>
  </description>
